    # Round 1: Evaluate
    '## 2. Research Problem Statement\nStandard framing theory posits that news headlines effectively constrain reader interpretation by narrowing the scope of information. However, current models often assume a universal mode of information processing. This research addresses the problem: **Does the efficacy of framing in news headlines decrease when the structural "framing" of the news conflicts with the ingrained "cognitive style" (Holistic vs. Analytic) of the reader’s culture?**\n\n## 3. Key Thesis\nI hypothesize that **High-Context/Holistic-thinking cultures possess an inherent "Cognitive Buffer" against explicit Western-centric framing.** While low-context/analytic cultures are highly susceptible to the specific "nudge" of an explicit frame (e.g., gain/loss, episodic/thematic), high-context readers are more likely to ignore the frame in favor of contextualizing the event within a broader, pre-existing mental network, thereby reducing the "framing effect."\n',
